article.headline: Stoudemire has 32 points in win
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Nobody is comparing Amare Stoudemire to Charles Barkley -- yet. If his current streak continues, that might change. Stoudemire had 32 points to become the first Phoenix player since Barkley in 1995-96 to score at least 20 in 10 consecutive games, and the Suns beat the Jason Kidd-less New Jersey Nets 87-74 Wednesday night. "The guys are very comfortable with me," the 2003 Rookie of the Year said after his 12th game since returning from a foot injury. "They've got a lot of confidence in my game, so that gives me a lot of confidence and a comfort area on the offensive end." Barkley had two 10-game, 20-point streaks during the 1995-96 season, his last in Phoenix. Joe Johnson scored 14 points, and Shawn Marion had 12 points, nine rebounds and six assists for the Suns, who won for the third time in four games. "We missed a lot of shots, but we really ground it out," coach Mike D'Antoni said. "Defensively, we did everything we talked about and even more, and then Amare had a huge night and got us over the hump." Richard Jefferson led the Nets with 26 points, and Kenyon Martin had 11 and 11 rebounds. But Phoenix had a 46-33 edge on the glass, with Jake Voskuhl getting 12 and Stoudemire 11. The annual meeting has had an edge since the Suns traded Kidd to New Jersey for Stephon Marbury in 2001. But this game lost part of its flavor when Phoenix sent Marbury to the New York Knicks on Jan. 5, and the rest when Kidd decided to skip it to rest his bruised left knee. Asked what happened to the Nets' transition game, Martin said, "It was sitting on the sidelines in a suit." The Nets beat Denver 95-91 Tuesday night without Kidd, but Kerry Kittles had a season-high 34 points in that one. This time, he scored only seven and no one but Jefferson picked up the slack. "We played them like JK was out there," Marion said. "We just took them out of everything they wanted to do, limited them to one shot and got out and executed our offense." The Nets tried to rally from a 17-point deficit late in the third quarter, and the Suns helped by missing eight of their first nine shots in the fourth. Lucious Harris had a 3-pointer and a free throw to spark a 12-3 surge that began with Jefferson's two free throws with 13 seconds left in the third quarter. Martin's free throw got the Nets to 73-65 with 7:37 to go, but Antonio McDyess had two free throws, Johnson made a jumper, Voskuhl made a free throw and Stoudemire had a layup in the next three minutes, extending the lead to 80-65 at the 4:33 mark. The Nets led only three times -- all in the first half. But Phoenix put on a 9-2 spurt after Jefferson made two free throws with 4:25 left in the second quarter, taking a 37-31 lead on Leandro Barbosa's 3-pointer with 59 seconds to go. "They really didn't jump out that big," Jefferson said. "It was a four- or five-point game at halftime. We were right there, but we couldn't hit shots down the stretch." Barbosa, who finished with 12 points, made another 3-pointer 16 seconds into the third quarter, starting a 17-8 run during which Stoudemire had eight points and three rebounds. Stoudemire finished the surge when he jumped, pulled the ball out of a defenders' fingertips in the air and muscled in an 11-footer, lifting Phoenix to a 54-41 lead at the 6:28 mark. The Suns, who outscored New Jersey 33-22 in the third, continued to build -- Marion and Voskuhl had three-point plays in the next run, and Voskuhl's opened a 70-53 lead with 31 seconds left in the period. "The third quarter really changed the game around," Nets coach Lawrence Frank said. "We were chasing them from then on."

Game notes
The Suns have won 10 straight at home against the Nets, whose last win in Phoenix was on March 13, 1993. ... The Suns activated F Maciej Lampe prior to the game. ... Jefferson planned to attend a ceremony at Phoenix Moon Valley High School, his prep alma mater, Thursday morning before the team flight to San Francisco. The school will honor Jefferson by retiring his No. 44 jersey. ... Stoudemire also has led Phoenix in scoring 10 consecutive games. Barkley did that in 11 straight in 1994-95. ... The Nets' 74 points were a season-low by a Phoenix opponent.
